{{unsourced|date=August 2010}} 
[[File:Moser Cicli chrome time trial bicycle (23986133770).jpg|thumb|Moser Cicli [[time trial bicycle]]]]
[[Francesco Moser]] began building [[racing bicycle]]s after his [[retirement]], as did many Italian bicycle racers, in a small workshop in [[Trento]], [[Italy]]. Production is 2,000-3,000 frames annually. 

Moser's frames are unique among Italian racing bicycles for being fillet [[brazing|brazed]] using [[silver solder]] rather than using lugs with brass brazing; silver solder never gets hot enough to weaken the tubing and thus bicycles constructed in this manner do not need to be reinforced with lugs, thus reducing the bicycle's weight. After brazing, each frame is hand filed and aligned on a digital alignment table. The smooth lines resulting from the lack of lugs are emphasized with a unicrown fork and an integrated seatpost, attached by an expander bolt in a manner similar to the handlebar stem.

{{DEFAULTSORT:Cicli, Moser}}

